Question 1 
Write the keystrokes needed for the commands in vi if the editor is currently in "Command" mode.
a. Delete 4 lines, starting from the current line.
      ans: 4dd
b. Search "cat" or "Cat" in the entire document
      ans: /\ccat ---\c case insensitive
c. Delete 6 characters, starting from the current position
      ans:6x
d. Switch to "Insert" mode.
      ans:i
e. Undo the most recent command.
      ans:u

Question 2
Briefly explain what the given command would do in vi if the editor is currently in command mode. (Hint:
Go try these commands and verify what they do).
a. :wq!
      ans:Forces the write and quits in read only file
      : -->enter in command line mode
      w -->save(write) the file
      q -->quit
      ! -->force the editor if the file is read only
b. :%s/cat/Cat/g
      ans:substitute the value
      : -->enter in command line mode
      % -->apply command for entire file
      s -->substitute
      g -->replace all occurance
c. 2fa
      ans: Moves the cursor to the second occurrence of the character a on the current line
d. yy (Hint: after doing this, go elsewhere in the file and do the command p)
      ans:copy the current line and paste
e. gg
      ans:moves the cursor to the first line
 
Question 3 
Write the keystrokes needed for these commands in editor VI. Assume that you want to accomplish
each task with as few keystrokes as possible.
a. Search backward
      ans:?pattern +enter
b. Cut text from the "mark" to the current position
      ans:d'`a
c. Move to the end of the line
      ans:$
d. Move forward one page
      ans:ctrl+F
e. Save buffered text to currently specified file
      ans:w

Question 4 
Briefly explain what each of the given commands would do in editor emacs. Note that the ^ symbol in
these commands represents the Control key.
a. :11,15s/Bangalore/Trivandrum/
      ans:Replaces the first occurrence of "Bangalore" with "Trivandrum" on lines 11 to 15 only.
b. :11,15s/Bangalore/Trivandrum/gc
      ans:Replaces all occurrences of "Bangalore" with "Trivandrum" on lines 11 to 15, asking for confirmation (c) before each replacement. (g = global, c = confirm)
c. :set nu
      ans:Displays line numbers for all lines in the file.
d. :q
      ans:Quits the editor. If there are unsaved changes, Vim will not quit and will display a warning.
e. :q!
      ans:Force quits the editor without saving any changes.
